Data reading

data <- read_excel("USA-median-mean-income-by-age.xlsx")
data <- na.omit(data)
data <- data[c("Age Group", "2017\ndollars(Male Mean)", "2017\ndollars(Female Mean)")]
print(colnames(data))
[1] "Age Group"                  "2017\ndollars(Male Mean)"  
[3] "2017\ndollars(Female Mean)"

Income with age

EDA

data$CurrentTotalMean <- (data$`2017\ndollars(Male Mean)` + data$`2017\ndollars(Female Mean)`) / 2

age_income_mean <- data %>%
  group_by(`Age Group`) %>%
  summarise(MeanIncome = mean(CurrentTotalMean, na.rm = TRUE))

# Plotting the relationship between age group and mean income
ggplot(age_income_mean, aes(x = `Age Group`, y = MeanIncome)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "#ff5722") +  # Use geom_col() if using ggplot2 version >= 2.2.0
  theme_minimal() + 
  labs(title = "Relationship Between Age Group and Mean Income",
       x = "Age Group",
       y = "Mean Income") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

Hypothesis

Null Hypothesis \(H_0\): There is no difference in mean income across different age groups. Alternative Hypothesis \(H_a\): There is a difference in mean income across different age groups.

new_data <- age_income_mean[-1, ]

Anova

age_income_mean$`Age Group` <- as.factor(age_income_mean$`Age Group`)
anova_result <- aov(MeanIncome ~ `Age Group`, data = age_income_mean)
summary(anova_result)
            Df    Sum Sq   Mean Sq
`Age Group`  6 931144825 155190804

Kruskal-Wallis

kruskal_test <- kruskal.test(MeanIncome ~ `Age Group`, data = age_income_mean)
kruskal_test

    Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test

data:  MeanIncome by Age Group
Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 6, df = 6, p-value = 0.4232

Therefore, based on this result, I would conclude that there is no significant difference in income across age groups since P-value is 0.4232, which is greater than the common alpha level of 0.05, at least not one detectable by this test with this data. This might be due to a truly non-existent difference, or it could be due to insufficient power (e.g., small sample sizes within groups, small differences between groups, high variability within groups, etc.).

Advanced analysis to get deeper insights

Does the mean income peak at a certain age group and then decline or does it consistantly increase with age?

age_group_mapping <- c("15 to 24" = 19.5, "25 to 34" = 29.5, "35 to 44" = 39.5, "45 to 54" = 49.5, "55 to 64" = 59.5, "65 and older" = 69.5)
new_data$AgeNumeric <- sapply(new_data$`Age Group`, function(x) age_group_mapping[x])
model <- lm(MeanIncome ~ AgeNumeric, data = new_data)

summary(model)

The p-value of 0.108 which is above the common alpha level of 0.05, suggesting that the relationship between age group and mean income is not statistically significant at the 5% level.

The rather small statistical significance may be due to a small sample size or high variability within age groups. With only 5 data points (after one was removed due to missingness), the power to detect significant effects is limited.
